Windup  <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#3B3B3B><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub13.ezboard.com/bthesafehouse.showLocalUserPublicProfile?login=adria>Adria</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Registered User</span><br> <font color=#FF0000>(10/11/00 11:54:21 pm)</font><br>    </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: What a bard is good for... &lt;sigh&gt;</span><hr size=1> I'm an ex-bard... what are bards good for?<br>
<br>
Haste and strength, mana and health regen, and resistance buffs. Maybe some damage and very little tanking.<br>
<br>
If the bard wants to snare or do crowd control they must devote themselves 100% to that task.<br>
<br>
It's amusing that two classes that can do many things: druids and necros, are so powerful. But another class that can do many things: the bard, is so weak. It's all an issue of mana. Verant designers can't work out how to balance a class that doesn't use mana (obvious by the bards level 39 and 43 songs). And so anyone who plays with or groups with a bard is forced to suffer.<br>
<br>
Anyone who has seen the tests Verant has done of the Level 15 bard song knows they are blind to the problem. There is at least a 50% resist rate on the song because there are two resistance checks. If the first check succeeds you get a success message even if the second check fails. The first check is 30% failure, the second check is an additional 30% failure. Of 100 tries, 70 will pass the first check. Of that 70, only 49 will pass the second check. So of 100 attempts, only 49 will pass both checks.<br>
<br>
51% resist rate is as intended? Oh well, all the more reason why myself and every other bard I knew from beta no longer play bards. <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#2f2f4f><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub13.ezboard.com/bthesafehouse.showLocalUserPublicProfile?login=vaeronazimyr>Vaeron Azimyr</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Registered User</span><br> <font color=#FF0000>(10/12/00 8:27:27 pm)</font><br>    </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: bard songs vs sneak/hide</span><hr size=1> Um, back on topic, I love grouping with bards.  But I hate hate HATE it when I'm trying to be sneaky somewhere and they decide to wander that way playing some song or other.  Terrible, and I'm glad they SAY they're going to look into it.<br>
<br>
Vaeron<br>
24th Circle Rogue - Saryrn<br>
18th Circle Rogue - Tholuxe Paells <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#3B3B3B><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub13.ezboard.com/umoshkiae.showPublicProfile?language=EN>Moshkiae</A>&nbsp; <IMG SRC=http://www.ezboard.com/ezgfx/globalBlack.gif BORDER=0 HEIGHT=10 WIDTH=10></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Registered User</span><br> <font color=#FF0000>(10/12/00 11:45:07 pm)</font><br>    </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: bard songs vs sneak/hide</span><hr size=1> Maybe I am too low, to really know which song breaks the sneak and hide, but through level 37 I have yet to see any Rogue use it.<br>
<br>
I am saddened to see the comments that all we can do is get Rogues killed. I would like to let some of you folks know that I single handedly have helped 6 Rogues top off their backstab skill, because I worked on making sure that I could position myself and get the taunts needed, so the Rogue could BS 3, 4, 5, times in any fight. How? Easy. I'm an instrument player! I like playing the AE's with the Horn, and in the earlier days the Dissonance with the Lute.<br>
<br>
I do recall once causing an inadvertant train in the Keep, because apparently the Rogue was doing her thing ... but she never told me. We had been discussing how I was going to break the Raider room with Charm, when she went out on her own. I already knew via Invisible song and Tracking what Picklaws were there and where.<br>
<br>
I really feel, that in a group situation, the only time a Bard is going to get a Rogue killed, or vice versa, it is because of the lack of communication, not otherwise. There is no Bard in this game I have ever met that will play a song in spite of someone else's abilities, or not take advantage of those abilities. I do not feel that a Rogue should purpposedly go do something that they felt was needed, without checking with the rest of the group ... yes I understand that it is in the Rogue's nature to be independent, but if you err and then die because of it, it is not necessarily the Bard's fault, or the group's.<br>
<br>
It's about communication, not finger pointing.<br>
<br>
It is, also, unfair, to expect every player in this game, regardless of level, to know everyone's abilities. So letting the others know is your responsibility, and I make a point of explaining what i am doing and why. <p>Moshkiae Soulmender - The Stryngs of Ayre - Veeshan Chapter
http://www.thestryngsofayre.com</p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#2f2f4f><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub13.ezboard.com/umadelinetz.showPublicProfile?language=EN>Madeline TZ</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Registered User</span><br> <font color=#FF0000>(10/13/00 12:08:21 am)</font><br>    <BR><img src=http://www.geocities.com/kaydenjadir/minidolly.jpg WIDTH=60 HEIGHT=60></td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: bard songs vs sneak/hide</span><hr size=1> Heh we're not blaming bards at all.  We all probably have some bard friends.  it's the mechanics of it all.  I mean should you listening cause you to falter in yer ability or help you improve?  Should depend on the music but this is not the case.  Any bard song breaks sneak/hide. <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#3B3B3B><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub13.ezboard.com/ubraxana.showPublicProfile?language=EN>Braxana</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Registered User</span><br> <font color=#FF0000>(10/13/00 6:54:55 am)</font><br>    </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> ANY spell will break sneak/hide</span><hr size=1> Very true, we're not picking on bards (per se). It's just that they tend to play songs ALL THE FREAKIN TIME. With no mana cost, why not, right? I despise grouping with bards for ~just~ this reason. Not their fault, I know, but the alternatives are (a) play the songs so I can never sneak/hide or (b) shut up the songs and no one gets the beneficial regen/mana regen effects. Well, we all know which option gets selected.<br>
<br>
Bards may be the most glaringly obvious culprit, but ~any~ spell can break a rogue's sneak/hide. Beneficial or not. Many is the time I announce, &quot;Prowling&quot; to the group and head out only to see &quot;Well-Intentioned-Cleric begins to cast a spell&quot;.... sure, I'm down a bubble of health, but I'll heal that WHILE I'm scouting for the next pull. BUT, as soon as I see that message, I fast-walk to a secure place because the inevitable magical sparkles are soon to come. Usually you can train casters not to cast on you once you're &quot;prowling&quot;, but they can SELECT whether you're affected by their spell; bards cannot.<br>
<br>
What's even worse, though, is that DETRIMENTAL spells (and songs) can break sneak/hide although they serve ~NO~ purpose. I don't know HOW many times I've been quietly healing the last 50% of health while hidden and a bard comes running past me with that damned AE attack song playing, a train of monsters on his tail. Not only is my sneak/hide broken, but it's broken JUST as a train roars by and I'm sitting down. Gee, wonder what happens next? :P<br>
<br>
Again, it's not JUST bards --- an AE spell by any caster will also make me visible, even though I get the &quot;Ignorant-Caster tries to cast a spell on you, but you are protected!&quot; message... protected? Yeh, right.<br>
<br>
They clearly can tell whether or not a spell SHOULD affect us, so how hard could it be to arrange things so that if a spell WILL NOT affect us for whatever reason....<br>
<br>
For example, attempted cast of Camo [silly druid] when not grouped --- beneficial spell, maybe, but we're not grouped so the spell won't take). <br>
<br>
...then sneak/hide is NOT broken.<br>
<br>
Of course the BEST solution would just be to declare that Sneak/Hide is ~only~ broken under the following conditions:<br>
<br>
(a) Movement with Sneak OFF breaks hide<br>
<br>
(b) Accessing a merchant (or bank) breaks hide (but not sneak) ~AND~ un-grays the Hide button so we KNOW Hide is broken<br>
<br>
(c) An attack, spell or physical, that DOES affect us ---- if we attack a monster and flee, and then we Sneak/Hide (perhaps to ease by some OTHER monsters) then the monster we attacked can of course still target us and any spell or physical attack that monster lands on us will break our sneak/hide.<br>
<br>
(d) Non-specific, hostile AE.... if a monster uses an Area effect attack (don't know many that do personally) then ~if~ we were in the area of effect and would be affected then Sneak/Hide would break.<br>
<br>
(e) Trap! Heh heh.... that's about all that traps DO in this game, is break Sneak/Hide. Kind of ironic that the only class that can ~reliably~ disable a trap (for all I know bards get this skill, too, capped at a low level) is also the class most affected by the trap.<br>
<br>
That's it. Other than that, Hide/Sneak should NOT break. PERIOD.<br>
<br>
If they fixed this problem, I know ~I~ would consider Bards in a more friendly light. <!--EZCODE EMOTICON START :) --><img src=http://www.ezboard.com/intl/aenglish/images/emoticons/smile.gif ALT=":)"><!--EZCODE EMOTICON END--> <br>
